ce:section.ce:para:
Crushed and dried C. procera leaves were used as raw materials in the preparation of CDs via hydrothermal treatment. To predict the maximum emission peak of the prepared CDs, their emission spectra were recorded by various exciting wavelengths ranging from 310 to 400 nm (Fig. S1 in Supporting information). The maximum emission peak was noticed at 416 nm at an excitation of 340 nm. The prepared CDs showed a dark-brown color when observed with the naked eye under daylight and bright fluorescence under the illumination by UV light at 365 nm (Fig. 1
                        ). A bright fluorescence emission with the highest emission wavelength at 416 nm and maximum excitation at 340 nm was observed via fluorescence spectroscopy. The stability of the CDs was checked regularly for up to 70 days (Fig. S2a), with minimum autofluorescence calculated in the leaf extract before and after hydrothermal treatment for complete carbonization of C. procera leaf sample with proper dilutions (Fig. S2b). The surface charge of the prepared CDs was measured with zeta potential, and found that the probe bears a charge around (−3.36 mV). Furthermore, and the surface charge with the addition of analyte (isoprothiolane) was changed to the almost neutral range to (−0.52 mV). The surface characteristics of the prepared CDs were investigated via FT-IR spectroscopy (Fig. S3 in Supporting Information). Strong peaks in the range of 2800–3500 cm−1 were observed, confirming the existence of OH– and N–H stretching vibrations. The weak absorption peak at 2923 cm−1 indicates C–H stretching, and the medium absorption peak at 1621 cm−1 indicates CO stretching for ketonic groups. The peaks around 1250–1300 cm−1 are a result of C–C stretching. The peaks around 1100 cm−1 contribute to CN bending vibrations. The prepared CDs have a strong peak around 320 nm (Fig. 1), implying that it was spawned by n → π* transition, which played the key role for a high QY of 71.90 – 71.95% according to the standard equation by using the slope method (Fig. S4 and Table 1
                        ).

To establish CDs as a probe for the sensing of pesticides, the synthesized CDs were treated with various pesticides (sulfosulfuron, fipronil, clodinafop, imidacloprid, isoproturon, carbendazim, thiamethoxam, hexaconazole, and tricyclazole; 1 mM) and their fluorescence spectra were recorded (Fig. 4
                        ). It was observed that the response of the CDs probe’s fluorescence spectra toward isoprothiolane was remarkable. The intense blue fluorescence peak of CDs was greatly quenched with isoprothiolane, whereas other pesticides did not show fluorescence enhancing or quenching. These demonstrate the capacity of the CDs probe’s fluorescence to detect isoprothiolane. It was also noted that increasing the concentration of isoprothiolane results in an emission of 416 nm intensity (Fig. 5
                        a). The emission intensity of the prepared CDs was gauged using various concentrations of isoprothiolane (1,000–0.05 µM). As revealed in (Fig. 5a), the emission intensity of CDs (I0/I) at 416 nm increased proportionally with the concentration of isoprothiolane (Fig. 5b). The calibration graph was plotted for emission intensity (I0/I) against isoprothiolane concentration (0.05–1,000 µM). From the graph, decent linearity with a correlation coefficient (R2) of 0.9921 was observed, where I0 represents emission intensity without isoprothiolane, and I represents the emission intensity with isoprothiolane (Fig. 5b). The LOD of the CDs was 11.58 nM (3.36 ppb) that is quite lower than the World Health Organization (WHO) and European Commission recommended estimates for dietary burden in rice grain. The analytical merit of the method was compared with the other analytical techniques, revealing the CDs-based fluorescence method exhibited a lower LOD than other analytical techniques (Table 3
                        ).

The surface of the synthesized CDs was enriched with an active organic group, i.e., –COH, –NH2, and –OH as confirmed by FTIR and XPS analyses. The phenomenon is achieved through the attachment of the carbonyl group with isoprothiolane resulting in the carbonyl group observed in the FTIR spectrum. Upon the hydrolysis of isoprothiolane to monoester isoprothiolane, which forms a strong electrostatic interaction with the (C–N) group of CDs forming a bond that traps surface energies, resulting in the fluorescence quenching of CDs (Fig. 6
                        ). As a result, the zeta potential of CDs was changed to almost neutral after the addition of isoprothiolane because C-N group of CDs bearing all the negative charge was depleted after the addition of pesticide. We can derive that the surface organic group of CDs plays a vital role in interacting with isoprothiolane, resulting in CDs-isoprothiolane nanoaggregates. Further, lifetime analysis of CDs and CDs conjugated with isoprothiolane reveals that the lifetime decreases from 2.591 ns to 2.528 ns (Fig. S7). This result confirms the quenching caused by the isoprothiolane due to the energy transfer from CDs. Therefore, it provides further information based on the Stern-Volmer equation:

                              I0/I = 1 + kqτ0[Q] = τ0/τ
